status_message_cleaned: Why study animal guts? Because their microbial communities play a role in digestion. status_message_cleaned: Why study animal guts? Because their microbial communities play a role in digestion. By learning more about how microbes assist in digestion, scientists could improve farm animals’ ability to digest food and grow faster and stronger. Because of the importance of digestion to growth, AAFC researchers are involved with several projects related to the microbiota in the guts of animals. Two are particularly interesting, because they focus on the guts of animals you might not think have much to do with agriculture: beavers and pandas.

status_message_cleaned: Tonight in – hear how science can turn fungi into pharmaceuticals at a presentation at the CEF. Ergot is a fungus that produces a potent toxic alkaloid that can harm plants, animals and people. However, when used in a proper dosage, compounds derived from ergot have been used to develop major drugs to treat hypertension, migraines, Parkinsons, and reproductive disorders, and can have anti-microbial and anti-tumor functions. Come learn more about ergot.

Isn’t this amazing?!? Back in the spring, AAFC scientists and the @AgMuseum participated in the @SoilCanada #SoilYourUndies campaign and buried some cotton underwear to test the soil’s microbiology; Healthy soil has lots of organisms that breakdown organic matter and fibres. We hoped to see some visible breakdown after our undies had been buried for several weeks.
The results we dug up were pretty conclusive – there was nothing left but the elastics!
If you want to test your own soil microbiology, instructions for the #SoilYourUndies campaign are available from the @SoilCouncil website:

link_name: Mapping agriculture from space: Is it really rocket science? - Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC)
status_message_cleaned: What do agriculture and rocket science have in common? Satellites! status_message_cleaned: Our potato genebank stores almost potato varieties. These come from a wide range of countries beyond just Canada. From Ireland to Peru, there's a large amount of diversity in the samples we keep. This is a part of our commitment to global food security - the preservation of the global food supply. As our scientist Dr. Benoit Bizimungu elains, "There are many potato varieties that aren’t grown today with traits that are of current or future interest to researchers and educators. text_original:
Our potato genebank stores almost 180 potato varieties. These come from a wide range of countries beyond just Canada. From Ireland to Peru, there's a large amount of diversity in the samples we keep. This is a part of our commitment to global food security - the preservation of the global food supply. 

As our scientist Dr. Benoit Bizimungu explains, "There are many potato varieties that aren’t grown today with traits that are of current or future interest to researchers and educators. Preserving these varieties ensures valuable attributes, and even those with known susceptibility to certain diseases, are kept for the development of future, better varieties." ow.ly/I2Ru30ck05q

What’s the difference between apple cider and apple juice? Preservability, for one.

Apple cider is raw apple juice that hasn’t been filtered to remove pulp and sediment. It starts to ferment in about a week, so it’s mostly a seasonal beverage. Pasteurization can extend its shelf-life but can also make it taste bitter.

Apple juice starts out as apple cider and is then filtered to remove pulp and sediment. It can take up to 20 hours to filter really clear apple juice! But not anymore. Click to read how electroflotation makes clear and stable apple juice. http://ow.ly/uXHs30aLwl6

text_original:
Dr. Mary MacArthur carried out groundbreaking work in the field of food dehydration and freezing in the 1940s, a time when such technologies were of vital importance in support of war efforts in Europe. She carried out thousands of experiments at Ottawa’s Central Experimental Farm, largely using a large dehydration tunnel built in 1942. Her research greatly improved the appearance and nutritional value of commercial dehydrated vegetables.

A testament to her achievements, Dr. MacArthur was the first woman to be named as a Fellow of the Agriculture Institute of Canada.

Learn more about the latest research being carried out by AAFC scientists in the field of vegetable preservation. http://ow.ly/lsz630aLvfU

She'll introduce you to Dr. Charles Forney and Dr. John DeLong, AAFC food storage scientist, to learn about research to keep apples and other fruits and vegetables fresh while in storage. Want to see where we work?

AAFC's Avril Vollenhoven is ready to take you inside the Kentville Research and Development Centre in Nova Scotia to learn about storing apples.

She'll introduce you to Dr. Charles Forney and Dr. John DeLong, AAFC food storage scientist, to learn about research to keep apples and other fruits and vegetables fresh while in storage. Then go into our apple refridgerated storage room to see a HarvestWatch kennel - a special storage sensor that lets apples "talk" to us.

Avril sure is a great tour guide! Will you follow the advice she got from our scientists on where to keep your apples at home? Tell us in the comments.

Join us Friday, August 19th, at 12:00 p.m. PDT (3pm EDT) for a Facebook Live event hosted by Dr. Joyce Boye, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations’ Special Ambassador for the International Year of Pulses 2016! An internationally acclaimed scientist, Dr. Boye is the Director of Research, Development and Technology, at Agriculture Canada’s Agassiz and Summerland Research and Development Centres. Dr. Boye will be delivering a 30 minute presentation touching on the importance of the International Year of Pulses and her role as ambassador, as well as the benefits of pulses, and the many products that can be derived from this highly diversifiable crop.

Have your questions ready! As Dr. Boye will also be answering questions received in the comments during the event.

link_name: Agassiz Research and Development Centre Open House
status_message_cleaned: Join us at the Agassiz Research and Development Centre’s open house as we help the Agassiz Farms Cycle Tour celebrate its th anniversary. Elore the world of agriculture through a series of public presentations, interactive displays, hay wagon rides and fun activities for the whole family. You will have the opportunity to meet Agriculture and Agri-Food scientists first hand and learn more about local research being conducted to improve the farming sector. Highlights include a kids’ zone with fun activities featuring snail races, so bring the whole family and enjoy this day loaded with agricultural fun. In addition, there will be cake and ice cream at :00 a.m. and :00 p.m. The first guests will receive tree seedlings on a first come, first served basis. Free admission and parking - rain or shine.

text_original:
Join us at the Agassiz Research and Development Centre’s open house as we help the Agassiz Farms Cycle Tour celebrate its 10th anniversary. Explore the world of agriculture through a series of public presentations, interactive displays, hay wagon rides and fun activities for the whole family. You will have the opportunity to meet Agriculture and Agri-Food scientists first hand and learn more about local research being conducted to improve the farming sector.

Highlights include a kids’ zone with fun activities featuring snail races, so bring the whole family and enjoy this day loaded with agricultural fun. In addition, there will be cake and ice cream at 11:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. The first 600 guests will receive tree seedlings on a first come, first served basis.

Free admission and parking - rain or shine.

link_name: Tweet chat: Let’s talk about bugs!
status_message_cleaned: Have you ever wondered how many species of insects there are? Are all bugs insects? How does bug science help Canadians? How do you keep an archive of millions of bugs? Let’s talk about bugs! We’re hosting a tweet chat with the curators of the Canadian National Collection of Insects, Arachnids and Nematodes (CNC), one of the largest collections of its kind in the world. The CNC serves Canadian scientists who investigate problems in the fields of agriculture, biodiversity, genetics, biological control and other various forms of integrated pest management, and is part of an international network for other researchers, educators and policy-makers. And they want to chat with you on Twitter about the work they do! You don’t need a Twitter account to follow along, but you will need one to ask a question or participate in the chat with our scientists.

text_original:
Have you ever wondered how many species of insects there are? Are all bugs insects? How does bug science help Canadians? How do you keep an archive of millions of bugs?

Let’s talk about bugs! We’re hosting a tweet chat with the curators of the Canadian National Collection of Insects, Arachnids and Nematodes (CNC), one of the largest collections of its kind in the world. The CNC serves Canadian scientists who investigate problems in the fields of agriculture, biodiversity, genetics, biological control and other various forms of integrated pest management, and is part of an international network for other researchers, educators and policy-makers. And they want to chat with you on Twitter about the work they do! 

You don’t need a Twitter account to follow along, but you will need one to ask a question or participate in the chat with our scientists.

link_name: Soil Fingerprinting: New Tool for Soil Analysis
status_message_cleaned: Today is Earth Day! Did you know that soil has a fingerprint and it's as unique as yours! It's based on a soil's chemical, physical, and biological properties. This innovation was developed by our research teams in Ontario and BC, collaborating with others in Germany. Unlike your fingerprint, a soil's fingerprint can change as its properties change. Comparing fingerprints from the same plot over time can help determine the health of soil and help soil conservation efforts. The soil fingerprinting framework tool is available in Ontario and will be available around the world in spring .

link_name: Soil Nutrients and Phosphorus: The Molecular View
status_message_cleaned: Chemistry! Phosphorus is an essential element required by all living organisms, including the crops grown by Canadian farmers. It occurs naturally in soil when organic matter breaks down into its component parts. When crops need extra phosphorus farmers can apply it directly as a fertilizer.
